COVID-19 Forest Plots

Jaqueline Passos, Izonete Cristina Guiloski e Henrique Laureano

Last modification on 2021-11-23 17:23:19

Número de participantes com COVID-19 e o sintoma de perda de olfato

Forest plot meta-analysis of the prevalence of olfactory dysfunctions in COVID-19 patients across studies. Random-effects models are presented. Individual study estimates are represented as black boxes on the continuous horizontal line, which represents the 95% CI.

Reference: Viechtbauer, W. (2010). Conducting meta-analyses in R with the metafor package. Journal of Statistical Software, 36(3), 1-48. https://doi.org/10.18637/jss.v036.i03

Anosmia: Cochran’s Q (Q=193.71, df=13, p<0.001), approximated from the chi-square distribution, is significant, and the \(I^{2}\) value of 90.8%, confirming the heterogeneity of the meta-analysis across the subjective studies. The pooled estimate for the prevalence for the overall cohort was 61% with a 95% CI of 49-72%.

Hyposmia: Cochran’s Q (Q=32.99, df=7, p<0.001), approximated from the chi-square distribution, is significant, and the \(I^{2}\) value of 94.4%, confirming the heterogeneity of the meta-analysis across the subjective studies. The pooled estimate for the prevalence for the overall cohort was 21% with a 95% CI of 9-32%.

Ageusia: Cochran’s Q (Q=328.23, df=7, p<0.001), approximated from the chi-square distribution, is significant, and the \(I^{2}\) value of 97.2%, confirming the heterogeneity of the meta-analysis across the subjective studies. The pooled estimate for the prevalence for the overall cohort was 46% with a 95% CI of 26-66%.

Dysgeusia: Cochran’s Q (Q=179.12, df=5, p<0.001), approximated from the chi-square distribution, is significant, and the \(I^{2}\) value of 96.8%, confirming the heterogeneity of the meta-analysis across the subjective studies. The pooled estimate for the prevalence for the overall cohort was 53% with a 95% CI of 24-82%.

Until 15 days: Cochran’s Q (Q=162.5, df=8, p<0.001), approximated from the chi-square distribution, is significant, and the \(I^{2}\) value of 93.4%, confirming the heterogeneity of the meta-analysis across the subjective studies. The pooled estimate for the prevalence for the overall cohort was 46% with a 95% CI of 30-61%.

After 15 days: Cochran’s Q (Q=763.63, df=13, p<0.001), approximated from the chi-square distribution, is significant, and the \(I^{2}\) value of 98.3%, confirming the heterogeneity of the meta-analysis across the subjective studies. The pooled estimate for the prevalence for the overall cohort was 44% with a 95% CI of 28-60%.
